            <div type="figure" subtype="drawing">
                <figure>
                    <head type="title"><title type="artwork" corresp="#JREHRENBREITSTEINRIVERMSIX">Vignette, Pines on Bank of the Rhine</title></head>
                    <figDesc>Pen and ink, approx. ? &#x00D7; ? cm (image only).</figDesc>
                    <p>The editors of the <ref type="note" subtype="bibliographical" target="library_edition_note.html">Library Edition</ref> 
                        describe the image as a &#x201C;sketch of a river, swollen and rushing between the hills&#x201D; 
                        (<ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.html#JRWORKSLE">Ruskin, <hi rend="italic">Works</hi></ref>, 2:358). 
                        A tiny figure clings to the tree growing from the foreground rocks. The sun is rising or setting over the turbulent water. 
                        <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName> probably meant the vignette to illustrate the &#x201C;impetuous <geogName corresp="#RHINE">Rhine</geogName>&#x201D; 
                        and &#x201C;<geogName corresp="#BLACKFOREST"></geogName>Schwartzwald pine&#x201D; described toward the end of the poem preceding this vignette.
                    </p>
                    <p>This drawing is listed as &#x201C;Pines&#x201D; in the <ref type="witness" target="account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_toc_msviii.php#ACCOUNTTOCEHRENBREITSTEIN"><title type="bibliography_text" corresp="#JRPROPOSEDTABLEOFCONTENTS">List of Proposed Additional Contents for the &#x201C;Account&#x201D;</title> (&#x201C;Coblentz&#x201D;)</ref>.</p>
                </figure>
